Title:     The new spin on CD-ROM: jukeboxes and ultrafast drives will
           get rid of the hassle.
             (includes related articles on offerings from Pioneer and on
             NEC's MultiSpin 3XE drive)  (one of four evaluations in
             'Cutting-Edge Multimedia')
Author:    White, Ron
Attached:  03M1T2.XLS  Dual-speed CD-ROM contenders.

Abstract:  A variety of top-of-the-line dual, triple- and quad-speed
           external SCSI CD-ROM drives are evaluated to determine which
           provides the best price and performance for multimedia tasks.
           The overall top-rated dual-speed drive of the six evaluated
           drives is Toshiba America Information Systems' TXM-3401E,
           which is priced at $640 or $800 with a microcomputer interface
           kit. It is praised for its excellent transfer rate and good
           reliability. The only drawback is that it does have a hefty
           price tag. Other highly-ranked dual-speed drives include
           Plextor's $439 DM-5028, which is very fast and is a good
           choice especially with large files, and Chinon America's $795
           CDX-535, which is praised for its speed and its inclusion of
           software demos from SelectWare. A variety of other CD-ROM
           options are discussed, such as purchasing a jukebox drive.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
Full Text:

Ever tried to open a file on a CD-ROM drive and been convinced your PC
had checked out for good? Meanwhile, there you sit, drumming your
fingers, waiting, waiting, waiting . . . .

That was then, this is now. CD-ROM drives still can't hold a candle to
hard disk access and transfer times, but they're finally getting a shot
of adrenaline. Dual-speed drives--clearly the standard now--are facing a
challenge from triple-and quad-speed drives like the new NEC MultiSpin
3Xe and the Pioneer DRM-1804X.

In every way, cutting-edge developments are set to catapult CD-ROM into
the mainstream. A couple of years ago, it would have been surprising if
you could find more than one CD--usually Microsoft Bookshelf or a
multimedia encyclopedia--that you'd always want handy. Now if you have
only one CD drive, it's tough to decide which disc to keep in it all the
time. There's still Bookshelf and an encyclopedia, but you also have the
complete documentation for your favorite application, whether it be
WordPerfect, Lotus 1-2-3, OS/2, or any of the other applications that are
starting to be distributed on CD. And there are scores of multimedia
collections of clip art, fonts, graphics, video, and sound that you'll
want online to include in your electronic documents. Add to that any
number of special-interest topics--from symphonies to UFOs--and one CD
drive is about as cutting edge as a dual-floppy system.

A smarter idea? Get a jukebox drive, like Pioneer's DRM-1804X. Pioneer's
drive holds up to 18 CDs and assigns a different drive letter to each.
Change drives and the drive head moves to the disc you requested. If
you've ever watched an old 45-rpm music jukebox at work, you've got the
idea. (See "How Jukebox CD-ROM Drives Work," below.) There is a delay, of
course, while one CD is moved away from the head and another is moved
into position. But it's still faster than you could unload and load a
single-disc CD drive--assuming you're organized enough to lay your hands
on a CD without having to search through a pile of desk clutter.

To find the cutting edge in CD-ROM drives, we tested the top dual-,
triple-, and quad-speed external SCSI drives. Pioneer's quad-speed drive
and NEC's triple-speed drives impressed us with their raw speed and
innovative designs. Toshiba's TXM-3401E was our overall favorite in
dual-speed drives, and dual-speed drives from Chinon and Plextor showed
us what some smart engineering can do. They still can't catch hard
drives, but they're a huge improvement over single-speed drives. And for
running multimedia CD applications, they're the only way to go.

Related Article

---------------

Pioneer's Quad-Speed Wonder

How many discs? No problem.

We understand. You're a complex, multifaceted individual--not just a
one-CD type of person. You want instant access to every disc you own. Do
we have the CD-ROM drive for you--the Pioneer DRM-1804X quad-speed
jukebox.

The 18 stands for 18 (count 'em, eighteen) CDs--which is the number of
discs the Pioneer can hold at one time. It doesn't give you instant
access to all of the CDs--the drive has only one read head, and takes
about 10 seconds to unmount one disc and mount another--but the process
is automatic. The drive contains three cartridges, each of which holds
six CDs. Each of the CDs is recognized as a separate drive by your
system. (Did you ever think you might reach a point where there might not
be enough letters in the alphabet to name all of your drives?)

Once a CD is in place, the Pioneer delivers a blistering seek time of 36
milliseconds (ms), a far cry from the standard of more than 300ms most
drives deliver.

The DRM-1804X's average transfer rate lagged slightly behind that of the
Chinon CDX-535 drive, but it was better than the CDX-535 at sustaining
high transfer rates with large files. It also demanded the least of the
PC's processor so other operations weren't slowed while the drive read a
disc.

At $2,495, the DRM-1804X costs a lot more than other drives. But what
else delivers 9 gigabytes of storage for that price? If multiple CDs are
part of your business, the DRM-1804X should be too.

