NEC's MultiSpin 3Xe Triple-Speed Drive

It's not the fastest, but we want one.

The futuristic design of NEC's MultiSpin 3Xe external triple-speed CD-ROM
drive easily makes it the sleekest CD-ROM drive we've seen. The drive's
double-door construction, designed to keep out dust, does not merely
open--it revolves. And an LED readout indicates the status of the drive
while it's being used to read either data or music CDs.

The MultiSpin 3Xe's performance isn't quite up to warp speed in some
areas. Two dual-speed CD-ROM drives--Chinon's CDX-535 and Toshiba's
TXM-3401E--beat it for sustained data transfers. The MultiSpin 3Xe
excelled in our test of Photo CD read times, however, averaging 7
seconds, compared with a range of 9 to 17 seconds for the other drives.
And for handling large, 400K files, only Pioneer's $2,495 quad-speed
DRM-1804X came close.

