How Jukebox CD-ROM Drives Work

Forget the CD shuffle--load up on discs.

Pioneer's DRM-1804X quad-speed CD jukebox drive works like a 1950s
jukebox: The drive moves to the selected disc tray and the tray pivots
out to insert or withdraw discs.

1. The jukebox is made up of one quad-speed CD-ROM drive and three
six-disc magazines.

2. To switch CDs, select a drive letter. The disc being read is released
from the drive, and its tray swings out then returns to its assigned
magazine.

3. The reader mechanism raises or lowers the drive to line it up with the
requested disc tray, and the tray swings out into the drive. The drive
clamps onto the disc, lifts it, and the spindle motor spins the disc.
